<h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
<div class="docbody" xml:lang="fra">
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Lahaie 18<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> fevr. 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Nos amis sont trs contents de la Dclaration ritre que je leur ai faite de votre part, &amp;c., &amp; vont agir en consquence auprs de la Cour de France, compris celle dEspagne, &amp; auprs de vos <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0272">[272<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0272.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>Excellences. Ils me paroissent persuads, que la mesure peut &amp; doit russir. Cependant,  tout vnement, ils me chargent de proposer encore la question suivante, pour obtenir l-dessus une rponse, favorable sil se peut, qui acheveroit de les mettre  laise, &amp; de les tranquilliser.</p>
<p>Q. Lorsque L. H. P. auront fait la proposition  la France, de signer conjointement avec lEspagne, lAmrique, &amp; les Pays-Bas unis, une Convention fonde sur les principes de la Neutralit arme pour le maintien de la libert de la Navigation; au cas que la France &amp; lEspagne parussent vouloir reculer &amp; diffrer une telle convention, ou Sy refuser avant la conclusion ou signature du Trait dfinitif; Mr. Dana, &amp; pendant son absence Mr. Adams, Soit seul &amp; come Ministre des Etats-Unis auprs de cette Rpublique, ou avec Mrs. ses Collegues, seroient-ils prets  signer une telle Convention provisionnelle, lorsquelle leur seroit propose de la part de L. H. P., entre les Etats-Unis &amp; les Pays-Bas unis?</p>
<p>On est persuad ici, que sans un Trait pareil, soit entre la France, lEspagne, les Etats-Unis &amp; les Pays-Bas-Unis, ou,  dfaut des deux premieres, au moins entre les deux dernieres Puissances, rien ne sauroit prvenir ni excuser la honte du Trait dfinitif pour cette Rpublique, qui nest entre en guerre que pour la libert des mers, &amp; qui en a fait une <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">conditio sine qua non</span> dans ses prliminaires de paix.</p>
<p>Il est fort  souhaiter que lun de ces deux arrangemens soit faisable  dfaut de lautre, parce que cela applaniroit tout dun coup, le chemin au Trait dfinitif. Il ne resteroit du moins dautre difficult que celle de Ngapatnam &amp; de la navigation par les Moluques, sur lesquelles je viens de lire le rapport des 17 Directeurs de la Compagnie, qui oppose les raisons les plus fortes  la cession de lun &amp; de lautre.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>Mon opinion est, sauf toujours votre meilleur avis, que votre acquiescement  la demande de ces Messieurs, peut se fonder sur ces trois choses: 1<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">0.</span> Sur la Rsolution des Etats-unis du 5 Octobr 1780, comunique par vous-mme  L. H. P. par Lettre du 8 Mars 1781;<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> &amp; sur ce que vous mavez marqu, que vos pouvoirs  cet gard nont point t rvoqus: 2<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">0.</span> sur ce que L. H. P. sont une des Parties de la Neutralit arme,  laquelle Mr. Dana attend quil plaise  une autre des Parties dadmettre les Etats-Unis: sur ce quil ne sagit, ce me semble, que de se garantir rciproquement, ce que vous avez dj sign dans le Trait damiti &amp; de Commerce conclu avec L. H. P.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0273">[273<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0273.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
<p>Je suis avec tous les sentimens dun vrai &amp; grand respect, &amp; en vous priant de les faire agrer aussi  LL. EE. Mrs. Franklin, Jay, Laurens, &amp; Brantzen, Monsieur / De V. E. le trs humble &amp; trs / obissant serviteur</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">C. W. f. Dumas</p>
</div></div>
<div class="translation">
<h2><span class="hi-all-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps; text-transform: lowercase;">Translation</span></h2>
<div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 18 February 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Our friends are very content with the renewed declaration that I have made to them on your part, etc., and will act accordingly with the courts of France and Spain, and with your excellencies. They seem to me convinced that the measure can and ought to succeed. But in any case, they instruct me again to ask the following question, in hopes of obtaining a favorable reply if possible, which would completely reassure them and put them at ease:</p>
<p>Question. When their High Mightinesses have made their proposal to France that it sign jointly with Spain, America, and the United Netherlands an agreement based on the principles of the Armed Neutrality in order to maintain the freedom of navigation, should France and Spain seem inclined to defer such an agreement or to reject it before the conclusion or signature of the definitive treaty, would Mr. Dana (and in his absence, Mr. Adams, either acting alone or as minister of the United States to this republic, or in conjunction with his colleagues) be prepared to sign a provisional agreement of this nature between the United States and the United Netherlands when it is proposed by their High Mightinesses?</p>
<p>We are convinced here that without such a treaty, whether between France, Spain, the United States, and the Netherlands, or, failing the two former, at least between the two latter powers, nothing could avert or excuse the shame of the definitive treaty for the Netherlands, which only went to war over the freedom of the seas and which made it a <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">conditio sine qua non</span> in its preliminaries to peace.</p>
<p>It is most desirable that one of these two solutions be feasible if the other should fail, because it would immediately smooth the path to a definitive treaty. At least then the only remaining difficulty would be Negapatam and navigation through the Moluccas. I have just read a report on this matter by the seventeen directors of the company, which argues strongly against ceding either.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>My opinionunless, of course, as always, you have a better oneis that your acquiescence to these gentlemens demands could be based on the following three things: 1. On the resolution made by the United States on 5 October 1780, which you yourself communicated to their High Mightinesses in a letter of 8 March 1781,<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> and in which you noted that your powers in this matter have not been revoked; 2. On the fact that their High Mightinesses are one of the parties involved in the Armed Neutrality, and that Mr. Dana is waiting until it pleases one of the other parties to admit <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0274">[274<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-14/ADMS-06-14-02-pb-0274.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>the United States; On the fact that it seems to me simply a matter of guaranteeing mutually what has already been signed in the treaty of friendship and trade concluded with their High Mightinesses.</p>
<p>I am, with all the sentiments of true and great respect, sir, and pray that you present them also to their excellencies Franklin, Jay, Laurens, and Brantsen, your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
<div class="closer"><p class="signed">C. W. f. Dumas</p>
</div></div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-sn">
   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: Paris  S. Excell<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">ce.</span> Mr. Adams, M. P. des E. U.; endorsed: M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Dumas Feb. 18 / 1783 / Ans<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">d</span> 23.</p>
</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0001">1</a>
   <p>For the substance of the Dutch East India Companys protest against any concessions in an Anglo-Dutch treaty with regard to the East Indies, which the company claimed would result in the rapid and total ruin of its trade and be in violation of the 1782 instructions to the Dutch peace negotiators, see the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Gazette dAmsterdam</span> of 21 Feb., and vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-13-02-0152#ADMS-06-13-02-pb-0248" class="pageNo">13:248</a>.</p>
</div>
        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-14-02-0176-fn-0002">2</a>
   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-14-02-0138&amp;expandNote=ADMS-06-14-02-0138-fn-0001#ADMS-06-14-02-0138-fn-0001" class="document"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s 29 Jan. letter to Dumas, note 1</a>, above.</p>
